# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alabama
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alabama/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:alabama/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:alabama/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:alabama/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:alabama/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:alabama/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:alabama/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:alabama/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:alabama/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:alabama/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:alabama/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:alabama/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:alabama/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:alabama/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:alabama/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:alabama/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:alabama/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:alabama/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:alabama/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:alabama/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:alabama/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:alabama/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:alabama/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:alabama/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:alabama/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:alabama/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:alabama/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:alabama/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:alabama/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] In 1853 the country contains 89 telegraph lines that stretched 23,261 miles (37,435 km).
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] When published in 1854, the country had an estimated 30,000 miles (48,000 km) of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:alabama/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:alabama/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama is nicknamed the *Yellowhammer State*, after the state bird.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama is also known as the "Heart of Dixie" and the "Cotton State".
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The state has diverse geography, with the north dominated by the mountainous Tennessee Valley and the south by Mobile Bay.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama's capital is Montgomery, and its largest city by population and area is Huntsville.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Its oldest city is Mobile, founded by French colonists (Alabama Creoles) in 1702 as the capital of French Louisiana.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Greater Birmingham is Alabama's largest metropolitan area and its economic center.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Politically, as part of the Deep South, or "Bible Belt", Alabama is a predominantly conservative state and is known for its Southern culture.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Within Alabama, American football, particularly at the college level, is part of the state's culture.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Originally the area of Alabama was home to many native tribes.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] It was a Spanish territory from the sixteenth century until the French acquired it in the early eighteenth century.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The British won the territory in 1763 until losing it in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Spain held Mobile as part of Spanish West Florida until 1813.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In December 1819, Alabama was recognized as a state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] During the antebellum period, Alabama was a major producer of cotton and widely used African American slave labor.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In 1861, the state seceded from the United States to become part of the Confederate States of America, with Montgomery acting as its first capital.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Following the American Civil War, it would suffer decades of economic hardship, in part due to agriculture and a few cash crops being the main driver of the state's economy.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Similar to other former slave states, Alabamian legislators employed Jim Crow laws from the late 19th century until the 1960s.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] High-profile events such as the Selma to Montgomery marches made the state a focal point of the civil rights movement in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] During and after World War II, the state's economy diversified with new industries.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In 1960, the establishment of NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville helped boost Alabama's economic growth by developing a local aerospace industry.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama's economy in the 21st century is based on automotive, finance, tourism, manufacturing, aerospace, mineral extraction, healthcare, education, retail, and technology.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Despite the economic and industrial growth in recent decades, Alabama typically ranks low in terms of health outcomes, educational attainment, and median household income.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The name of the Alabama River and state is derived from the Alabama people, a Muskogean-speaking tribe whose members lived just below the confluence of the Coosa and Tallapoosa rivers on the upper reaches of the river.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In the Alabama language, the word for a person of Alabama lineage is *Albaamo* (or variously *Albaama* or *Albàamo* in different dialects; the plural form is *Albaamaha*).
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The word's spelling varies significantly among historical sources.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The first usage appears in three accounts of the Hernando de Soto expedition of 1540: Garcilaso de la Vega used *Alibamo*, while the Knight of Elvas and Rodrigo Ranjel wrote *Alibamu* and *Limamu*, respectively, in transliterations of the term.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] As early as 1702, the French called the tribe the *Alibamon*, with French maps identifying the river as *Rivière des Alibamons*.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Other spellings of the name have included *Alibamu*, *Alabamo*, *Albama*, *Alebamon*, *Alibama*, *Alibamou*, *Alabamu*, and *Allibamou*.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The use of state names derived from Native American languages is common in the U.S.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] An estimated 26 states have names of Native American origin.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Some scholars suggest the word comes from the Choctaw *alba* (meaning 'plants' or 'weeds') and *amo* (meaning 'to cut', 'to trim', or 'to gather').
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The meaning may have been 'clearers of the thicket' or 'herb gatherers', referring to clearing land for cultivation or collecting medicinal plants.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The state has numerous place names of Native American origin.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] An 1842 article in the *Jacksonville Republican* proposed it meant 'Here We Rest'.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] This notion was popularized in the 1850s through the writings of Alexander Beaufort Meek.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Experts in the Muskogean languages have not found any evidence to support such a translation.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Indigenous peoples of varying cultures lived in the area for thousands of years before the advent of European colonization.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Trade with the northeastern tribes by the Ohio River began during the Burial Mound Period (1000 BC – 700 AD) and continued until European contact.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The agrarian Mississippian culture covered most of the state from 1000 to 1600 AD, with one of its major polities centered around what is now the Moundville Archaeological Site in Moundville, Alabama.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] This is the second-largest complex of the classic Middle Mississippian era, after Cahokia in present-day Illinois, which was the earliest center of the culture.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Analysis of artifacts from archaeological excavations at Moundville were the basis of scholars' formulating the characteristics of the Southeastern Ceremonial Complex (SECC).
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Contrary to popular belief, the SECC appears to have no direct links to Mesoamerican culture but developed independently.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The Ceremonial Complex represents a major component of the religion of the Mississippian peoples; it is one of the primary means by which their religion is understood.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Among the historical tribes of Native American people living in present-day Alabama at the time of European contact were the Cherokee, an Iroquoian language people; and the Muskogean-speaking Alabama (*Alibamu*), Chickasaw, Choctaw, Creek, and Koasati.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] While part of the same large language family, the Muskogee tribes developed distinct cultures and languages.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The Spanish were the first Europeans to reach Alabama during their exploration of North America in the 16th century.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The expedition of Hernando de Soto passed through Mabila and other parts of the state in 1540.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] More than 160 years later, the French founded the region's first European settlement at Old Mobile in 1702.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The city was moved to the current site of Mobile in 1711.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] This area was claimed by the French from 1702 to 1763 as part of La Louisiane.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] After the French lost to the British in the Seven Years' War, it became part of British West Florida from 1763 to 1783.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] After the U.S. victory in the American Revolutionary War, the territory was divided between the United States and Spain.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The latter retained control of this western territory from 1783 until the surrender of the Spanish garrison at Mobile to U.S. forces on April 13, 1813.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Thomas Bassett, a loyalist to the British monarchy during the Revolutionary era, was one of the earliest white settlers in the state outside Mobile.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] He settled in the Tombigbee District during the early 1770s.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The district's boundaries were roughly limited to the area within a few miles of the Tombigbee River and included portions of what is today southern Clarke County, northernmost Mobile County, and most of Washington County.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] What are now Baldwin and Mobile counties became part of Spanish West Florida in 1783, part of the independent Republic of West Florida in 1810, and finally part of the Mississippi Territory in 1812.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Most of what is now the northern two-thirds of Alabama was known as the Yazoo lands beginning during the British colonial period.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] It was claimed by the Province of Georgia from 1767 onwards.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Following the American Revolutionary War, it remained a part of Georgia, although heavily disputed.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] With the exception of the area around Mobile and the Yazoo lands, what is now the lower one-third of Alabama was made part of the Mississippi Territory when it was organized in 1798.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The Yazoo lands were added to the territory in 1804, following the Yazoo land scandal.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Spain kept a claim on its former Spanish West Florida territory in what would become the coastal counties until the Adams–Onís Treaty officially ceded it to the U.S. in 1819.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The creation of the Mississippi Territory quickly prompted debates over its division.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Amid pressure from white southerners who sought the establishment of two slave states, Congress formed the Alabama Territory from the eastern half of the Mississippi Territory on March 3, 1817.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The legislation appointed William Wyatt Bibb of Georgia as the first governor of the newly designated Alabama Territory.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Before Mississippi's admission to statehood on December 10, 1817, the more sparsely settled eastern half of the territory was separated and named the Alabama Territory.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The United States Congress created the Alabama Territory on March 3, 1817.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Stephens, now abandoned, served as the territorial capital from 1817 to 1819.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama was admitted as the 22nd state on December 14, 1819, with Congress selecting Huntsville as the site for the first Constitutional Convention.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] From July 5 to August 2, 1819, delegates met to prepare the new state constitution.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Huntsville served as temporary capital from 1819 to 1820, when the seat of government moved to Cahaba in Dallas County.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Cahaba, now a ghost town, was the first permanent state capital from 1820 to 1825.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The Alabama Fever land rush was underway when the state was admitted to the Union, with settlers and land speculators pouring into the state to take advantage of fertile land suitable for cotton cultivation.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Part of the frontier in the 1820s and 1830s, its constitution provided for universal suffrage for white men.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Southeastern planters and traders from the Upper South brought slaves with them as the cotton plantations in Alabama expanded.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The economy of the central Black Belt (named for its dark, productive soil) was built around large cotton plantations whose owners' wealth grew mainly from slave labor.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The area also drew many poor, disenfranchised people who became subsistence farmers.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama had an estimated population of under 10,000 people in 1810, but it increased to more than 300,000 people by 1830.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Most Native American tribes were completely removed from the state within a few years of the passage of the Indian Removal Act by Congress in 1830.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] From 1826 to 1846, Tuscaloosa served as Alabama's capital.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] On January 30, 1846, the Alabama legislature announced it had voted to move the capital city from Tuscaloosa to Montgomery.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The first legislative session in the new capital met in December 1847.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] A new capitol building was erected under the direction of Stephen Decatur Button of Philadelphia.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The first structure burned down in 1849, but was rebuilt on the same site in 1851.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] This second capitol building in Montgomery remains to the present day.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] It was designed by Barachias Holt of Exeter, Maine.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] By 1860, the population had increased to 964,201 people, of which nearly half, 435,080, were enslaved African Americans, and 2,690 were free people of color.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] On January 11, 1861, Alabama declared its secession from the Union.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] After remaining an independent republic for a few days, it joined the Confederate States of America.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The Confederacy's capital was initially at Montgomery.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama was heavily involved in the American Civil War.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Although comparatively few battles were fought in the state, Alabama contributed about 120,000 soldiers to the war effort.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] A company of cavalry soldiers from Huntsville, Alabama, joined Nathan Bedford Forrest's battalion in Hopkinsville, Kentucky.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The company wore new uniforms with yellow trim on the sleeves, collar and coattails.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] This led to them being greeted with "Yellowhammer", and the name later was applied to all Alabama troops in the Confederate Army.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama's slaves were freed by the 13th Amendment in 1865.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama was under military rule from the end of the war in May 1865 until its official restoration to the Union in 1868.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] From 1867 to 1874, with most white citizens barred temporarily from voting and freedmen enfranchised, many African Americans emerged as political leaders in the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama was represented in Congress during this period by three African-American congressmen: Jeremiah Haralson, Benjamin S.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Following the war, the state remained chiefly agricultural, with an economy tied to cotton.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] During the Reconstruction era, state legislators ratified a new state constitution in 1868 which created the state's first public school system and expanded women's rights.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Legislators funded numerous public road and railroad projects, although these were plagued with allegations of fraud and misappropriation.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Organized insurgent, resistance groups tried to suppress the freedmen and Republicans.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] These groups included The Ku Klux Klan, the Pale Faces, Knights of the White Camellia, Red Shirts, and the White League.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Reconstruction in Alabama ended in 1874, when the Democrats regained control of the legislature and governor's office through an election dominated by fraud and violence.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] They wrote another constitution in 1875, and the legislature passed the Blaine Amendment, prohibiting public money from being used to finance religiously affiliated schools.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The same year, legislation was approved that called for racially segregated schools.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Railroad passenger cars were segregated in 1891.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The 1901 constitution required racial segregation of public schools.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] By 1903 only 2,980 African Americans were registered in Alabama, although at least 74,000 were literate.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] This compared to more than 181,000 African Americans eligible to vote in 1900.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The numbers dropped even more in later decades.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The state legislature passed additional racial segregation laws related to public facilities into the 1950s: jails were segregated in 1911; hospitals in 1915; toilets, hotels, and restaurants in 1928; and bus stop waiting rooms in 1945.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] While the planter class had persuaded poor whites to vote for this legislative effort to suppress black voting, the new restrictions resulted in their disenfranchisement as well, due mostly to the imposition of a cumulative poll tax.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] By 1941, whites constituted a slight majority of those disenfranchised by these laws: 600,000 whites vs.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Nearly all blacks had lost the ability to vote.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Despite numerous legal challenges which succeeded in overturning certain provisions, the state legislature would create new ones to maintain disenfranchisement.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The exclusion of blacks from the political system persisted until after passage of federal civil rights legislation in 1965 to enforce their constitutional rights as citizens.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The rural-dominated Alabama legislature consistently underfunded schools and services for the disenfranchised African Americans, but it did not relieve them of paying taxes.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Partially as a response to chronic underfunding of education for African Americans in the South, the Rosenwald Fund began funding the construction of what came to be known as Rosenwald Schools.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In Alabama, these schools were designed, and the construction partially financed with Rosenwald funds, which paid one-third of the construction costs.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The fund required the local community and state to raise matching funds to pay the rest.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Black residents effectively taxed themselves twice, by raising additional monies to supply matching funds for such schools, which were built in many rural areas.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] They often donated land and labor as well.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Beginning in 1913, the first 80 Rosenwald Schools were built in Alabama for African American children.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] A total of 387 schools, seven teachers' houses, and several vocational buildings were completed by 1937 in the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Several of the surviving school buildings in the state are now listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Reflecting this emigration, the population growth rate in Alabama (see "historical populations" table below) dropped by nearly half from 1910 to 1920.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] At the same time, many rural people migrated to the city of Birmingham to work in new industrial jobs.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Birmingham experienced such rapid growth it was called the "Magic City".
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] By 1920, Birmingham was the 36th-largest city in the United States.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Heavy industry and mining were the basis of its economy.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Its residents were under-represented for decades in the state legislature, which refused to redistrict after each decennial census according to population changes, as it was required by the state constitution.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] This did not change until the late 1960s following a lawsuit and court order.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Industrial development related to the demands of World War II brought a level of prosperity to the state not seen since before the civil war.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Rural workers poured into the largest cities in the state for better jobs and a higher standard of living.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] One example of this massive influx of workers occurred in Mobile.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Between 1940 and 1943, more than 89,000 people moved into the city to work for war-related industries.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Cotton and other cash crops faded in importance as the state developed a manufacturing and service base.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Despite massive population changes in the state from 1901 to 1961, the rural-dominated legislature refused to reapportion House and Senate seats based on population, as required by the state constitution to follow the results of decennial censuses.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] They held on to old representation to maintain political and economic power in agricultural areas.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] One result was that Jefferson County, containing Birmingham's industrial and economic powerhouse, contributed more than one-third of all tax revenue to the state, but did not receive a proportional amount in services.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Urban interests were consistently underrepresented in the legislature.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In the United States Supreme Court cases of *Baker v.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Sims* (1964), the court ruled that the principle of "one man, one vote" needed to be the basis of both houses of state legislatures, and that their districts had to be based on population rather than geographic counties.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] African Americans continued to press in the 1950s and 1960s to end disenfranchisement and segregation in the state through the civil rights movement, including legal challenges.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Board of Education* that public schools had to be desegregated, but Alabama was slow to comply.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] During the 1960s, under Governor George Wallace, Alabama resisted compliance with federal demands for desegregation.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The civil rights movement had notable events in Alabama, including the Montgomery bus boycott (1955–1956), Freedom Rides in 1961, and 1965 Selma to Montgomery marches.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] These contributed to Congressional passage and enactment of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965 by the U.S.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Legal segregation ended in the states in 1964, although Jim Crow customs often continued until specifically challenged in court.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] According to *The New York Times*, by 2017, many of Alabama's African Americans were living in Alabama's cities such as Birmingham and Montgomery.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Also, the Black Belt region across central Alabama "is home to largely poor counties that are predominantly African-American.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In 1972, for the first time since 1901, the legislature completed the congressional redistricting based on the decennial census.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] This benefited the urban areas that had developed, as well as all in the population who had been underrepresented for more than sixty years.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Other changes were made to implement representative state house and senate districts.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama has made some changes since the late 20th century and has used new types of voting to increase representation.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In the 1980s, an omnibus redistricting case, *Dillard v.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Crenshaw County*, challenged the at-large voting for representative seats of 180 Alabama jurisdictions, including counties and school boards.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] At-large voting had diluted the votes of any minority in a county, as the majority tended to take all seats.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Despite African Americans making up a significant minority in the state, they had been unable to elect any representatives in most of the at-large jurisdictions.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] As part of settlement of this case, five Alabama cities and counties, including Chilton County, adopted a system of cumulative voting for election of representatives in multi-seat jurisdictions.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] This has resulted in more proportional representation for voters.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In another form of proportional representation, 23 jurisdictions use limited voting, as in Conecuh County.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In 1982, limited voting was first tested in Conecuh County.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Together use of these systems has increased the number of African Americans and women being elected to local offices, resulting in governments that are more representative of their citizens.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Beginning in the 1960s, the state's economy shifted away from its traditional lumber, steel, and textile industries because of increased foreign competition.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] However, the state, particularly Huntsville, benefited from the opening of the George C.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Marshall Space Flight Center in 1960, a major facility in the development of the Saturn rocket program and the space shuttle.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Technology and manufacturing industries, such as automobile assembly, replaced some of the state's older industries in the late twentieth century, but the state's economy and growth lagged behind other states in the area, such as Georgia and Florida.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In 2001, Alabama Supreme Court chief justice Roy Moore installed a statue of the Ten Commandments in the capitol in Montgomery.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Circuit Court ordered the statue removed, but Moore refused to follow the court order, which led to protests around the capitol in favor of keeping the monument.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The monument was removed in August 2003.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] A few natural disasters have occurred in the state in the twenty-first century.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In 2004, Hurricane Ivan, a category 3 storm upon landfall, struck the state and caused over $18 billion of damage.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] It was among the most destructive storms to strike the state in its modern history.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] A super outbreak of 62 tornadoes hit the state in April 2011 and killed 238 people, devastating many communities.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama is the thirtieth-largest state in the United States with 52,419 square miles (135,760 km2) of total area: 3.2% of the area is water, making Alabama 23rd in the amount of surface water, also giving it the second-largest inland waterway system in the United States.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] About three-fifths of the land area is part of the Gulf Coastal Plain, a gentle plain with a general descent towards the Mississippi River and the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The North Alabama region is mostly mountainous, with the Tennessee River cutting a large valley and creating numerous creeks, streams, rivers, mountains, and lakes.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama is bordered by the states of Tennessee to the north, Georgia to the east, Florida to the south, and Mississippi to the west.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama has a coastline on the Gulf of Mexico, in the extreme southern edge of the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The state ranges in elevation from sea level at Mobile Bay to more than 2,000 feet (610 m) in the northeast, to Mount Cheaha at 2,413 ft (735 m).
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama's land consists of 22 million acres (89,000 km2) of forest or 67% of the state's total land area.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Suburban Baldwin County, along the Gulf Coast, is the largest county in the state in both land area and water area.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Additionally, Alabama has four National Forests: Conecuh, Talladega, Tuskegee, and William B.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama also contains the Natchez Trace Parkway, the Selma To Montgomery National Historic Trail, and the Trail of Tears National Historic Trail.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] A 5-mile (8 km)-wide meteorite impact crater is located in Elmore County, just north of Montgomery.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] This is the Wetumpka crater, the site of "Alabama's greatest natural disaster".
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] A 1,000-foot (300 m)-wide meteorite hit the area about 80 million years ago.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In 2002, Christian Koeberl with the Institute of Geochemistry University of Vienna published evidence and established the site as the 157th recognized impact crater on Earth.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The state is classified as humid subtropical (*Cfa*) under the Köppen climate classification.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The average annual temperature is 64 °F (18 °C).
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Temperatures tend to be warmer in the southern part of the state with its proximity to the Gulf of Mexico, while the northern parts of the state, especially in the Appalachian Mountains in the northeast, tend to be slightly cooler.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Generally, Alabama has very hot summers and mild winters with copious precipitation throughout the year.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama receives an average of 56 inches (1,400 mm) of rainfall annually and enjoys a lengthy growing season of up to 300 days in the southern part of the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Summers in Alabama are among the hottest in the U.S., with high temperatures averaging over 90 °F (32 °C) throughout the summer in some parts of the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama is also prone to tropical storms and hurricanes.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Areas of the state far away from the Gulf are not immune to the effects of the storms, which often dump tremendous amounts of rain as they move inland and weaken.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] South Alabama reports many thunderstorms.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The Gulf Coast, around Mobile Bay, averages between 70 and 80 days per year with thunder reported.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] This activity decreases somewhat further north in the state, but even the far north of the state reports thunder on about 60 days per year.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Occasionally, thunderstorms are severe with frequent lightning and large hail; the central and northern parts of the state are most vulnerable to this type of storm.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama ranks ninth in the number of deaths from lightning and tenth in the number of deaths from lightning strikes per capita.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama, along with Oklahoma and Iowa, has the most confirmed F5 and EF5 tornadoes of any state, according to statistics from the National Climatic Data Center for the period January 1, 1950, to June 2013.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Several long-tracked F5/EF5 tornadoes have contributed to Alabama reporting more tornado fatalities since 1950 than any other state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The state was affected by the 1974 Super Outbreak and was devastated tremendously by the 2011 Super Outbreak.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The 2011 Super Outbreak produced a record amount of tornadoes in the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The peak season for tornadoes varies from the northern to southern parts of the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama is one of the few places in the world that has a secondary tornado season in November and December besides the typically severe spring.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The northern part—along the Tennessee River Valley—is most vulnerable.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The area of Alabama and Mississippi most affected by tornadoes is sometimes referred to as Dixie Alley, as distinct from the Tornado Alley of the Southern Plains.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Winters are generally mild in Alabama, as they are throughout most of the Southeastern United States, with average January low temperatures around 40 °F (4 °C) in Mobile and around 32 °F (0 °C) in Birmingham.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Although snow is a rare event in much of Alabama, areas of the state north of Montgomery may receive a dusting of snow a few times every winter, with an occasional moderately heavy snowfall every few years.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Historic snowfall events include New Year's Eve 1963 snowstorm and the 1993 Storm of the Century.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The annual average snowfall for the Birmingham area is 2 inches (51 mm) per year.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In the southern Gulf coast, snowfall is less frequent, sometimes going several years without any snowfall.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama's highest temperature of 112 °F (44 °C) was recorded on September 5, 1925, in the unincorporated community of Centerville.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The record low of −27 °F (−33 °C) occurred on January 30, 1966, in New Market.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The state is usually ranked among the top in nation for its range of overall biodiversity.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama is in the subtropical coniferous forest biome and once boasted huge expanses of pine forest, which still form the largest proportion of forests in the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] It currently ranks fifth in the nation for the diversity of its flora.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] It is home to nearly 4,000 pteridophyte and spermatophyte plant species.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Indigenous animal species in the state include 62 mammal species, 93 reptile species, 73 amphibian species, roughly 307 native freshwater fish species, and 420 bird species that spend at least part of their year within the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Invertebrates include 97 crayfish species and 383 mollusk species.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] 113 of these mollusk species have never been collected outside the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] As of 2010, the state contains 461 municipalities, consisting of 174 cities and 287 towns.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Covering only 9.6% of Alabama's land mass, its municipalities are home to 60.4% of its population.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Montgomery, the state's capital, is the third-most populous settlement in Alabama; and the most populous city is Huntsville.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Census Bureau, the state contains 12 metropolitan statistical areas.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama's largest metropolitan area was Greater Birmingham.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] At the 1800 United States census, Alabama had a population of 1,250 people.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Since then, the state has continued to experience population growth with every U.S. census.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] According to the 2020 United States census the population of Alabama was 5,024,279, which represents an increase of 244,543 or 5.12%, since the 2010 census.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] This includes a natural increase since the last census of 121,054 (502,457 births minus 381,403 deaths) and an increase due to net migration of 104,991 into the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] According to statistics from 2012, immigration from outside the U.S. resulted in a net increase of 31,180 people, and migration within the country produced a net gain of 73,811 people.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The state had 108,000 foreign-born residents (2.4% of the state population), of which an estimated 22.2% were undocumented (24,000).
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The top countries of origin for immigrants were Mexico, China, India, Germany and Guatemala as of 2018.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 3,752 homeless people in Alabama.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] With a population density of 99.2 people per square mile as of 2020, the majority of the state's population lives in North, Central, and South Alabama, spread throughout the Huntsville, Birmingham, Montgomery and Mobile metropolitan statistical areas.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The center of population of Alabama is located in Chilton County, outside the town of Jemison.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Many American Indian tribes such as the Cherokee, Chickasaw, Choctaw, and Coushatta inhabited present-day Alabama before European colonization.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] With Spanish, French, and British colonization of Alabama, white and black Americans migrated to the area.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] From European colonization to U.S. statehood, Alabama's population grew to become increasingly non-Hispanic white and African American.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] By the 2020 census, Alabama's total racial and ethnic population was 66.5% non-Hispanic white and 26.9% African American, with a growing Hispanic and Latino population of 5.3%.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabamians citing "American" ancestry are of overwhelmingly English extraction.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Demographers estimate that a minimum of 20–23% of people in Alabama are of predominantly English ancestry and state that the figure is probably much higher.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In the 1980 census, 1,139,976 people in Alabama cited that they were of English ancestry out of a total state population of 2,824,719 making them 41% of the state at the time and the largest ethnic group.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama has the 5th-highest black and African American population among U.S. states at 25.8% alone as of 2020.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In 2011, 46.6% of Alabama's population younger than age 1 were minorities.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The Scots-Irish were the largest non-English immigrant group from the British Isles before the American Revolution, and many settled in the South, later moving into the Deep South as it was developed.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In 1984, under the Davis–Strong Act, the state legislature established the Alabama Indian Affairs Commission.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Indigenous groups within the state had increasingly been demanding recognition as ethnic groups and seeking an end to discrimination.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Given the long history of slavery and associated racial segregation, the Native American or American Indian peoples, who have sometimes been of mixed race, have insisted on having their cultural identification respected.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In the past, their self-identification was often overlooked as the state tried to impose a binary breakdown of society into white and black.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The state has officially recognized nine American Indian tribes in the state, descended mostly from the Five Civilized Tribes of the American Southeast.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The state government has promoted recognition of American Indian contributions to the state, including the designation in 2000 for Columbus Day to be jointly celebrated as American Indian Heritage Day.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In 2020, 33,625 identified as being Native American alone, and 97,405 did in combination with one or more other races.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] According to the 2022 American Community Survey's estimates, approximately 94% of Alabamians speak English as their sole language, while 6% spoke a language other than English.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Of other languages, the majority of its multilingual population speaks Spanish (3.8%).
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In a separate 2021 study by the American University Washington College of Law, Spanish was spoken by 156,656 residents.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Following, Korean, Vietnamese, Mandarin and Cantonese, German, French, and Tagalog were the most-spoken languages; among its French-speaking population, the majority have preserved their language since French colonization.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Pre-colonial and present-day Alabamians have adhered to multiple religions including Native American and African diaspora religions, and predominantly Christianity with the establishment of Spanish missions in Florida.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Other faiths including Judaism, Islam, and Indian religions were introduced since European colonization and American settlement.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] According to a 2023 Public Religion Research Institute survey, an estimated 80% of the adult population were Christian.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In the 2008 American Religious Identification Survey, 86% of Alabama respondents reported their religion as Christian, including 6% Catholic, with 11% as having no religion.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The composition of other traditions is 0.5% Mormon, 0.5% Jewish, 0.5% Muslim, 0.5% Buddhist, and 0.5% Hindu.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama is located in the middle of the Bible Belt, a region of numerous Protestant Christians.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama has been identified as one of the most religious states in the United States, with about 58% of the population attending church regularly.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] A majority of people in the state identify as Evangelical Protestant.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] As of 2010, the three largest denominational groups in Alabama are the Southern Baptist Convention, The United Methodist Church, and non-denominational Evangelical Protestant.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In Alabama, the Southern Baptist Convention has the highest number of adherents with 1,380,121; this is followed by the United Methodist Church with 327,734 adherents, non-denominational Evangelical Protestant with 220,938 adherents, and the Catholic Church with 150,647 adherents.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Many Baptist and Methodist congregations became established in the Great Awakening of the early 19th century, when preachers proselytized across the South.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The Assemblies of God had almost 60,000 members, the Churches of Christ had nearly 120,000 members.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In a 2007 survey, nearly 70% of respondents could name all four of the Christian Gospels.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Of those who indicated a religious preference, 59% said they possessed a "full understanding" of their faith and needed no further learning.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In a 2007 poll, 92% of Alabamians reported having at least some confidence in churches in the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Although in much smaller numbers, many other religious faiths are represented in the state as well, including Judaism, Islam, Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism, the Baháʼí Faith, and Unitarian Universalism.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Jews have been present in what is now Alabama since 1763, during the colonial era of Mobile, when Sephardic Jews immigrated from London.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The oldest Jewish congregation in the state is Congregation Sha'arai Shomayim in Mobile.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] It was formally recognized by the state legislature on January 25, 1844.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Later immigrants in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries tended to be Ashkenazi Jews from eastern Europe.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Jewish denominations in the state include two Orthodox, four Conservative, ten Reform, and one Humanistic synagogue.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Muslims have been increasing in Alabama, with 31 mosques built by 2011, many by African-American converts.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] There are six Dharma centers and organizations for Theravada Buddhists.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Most monastic Buddhist temples are concentrated in southern Mobile County, near Bayou La Batre.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] This area has attracted an influx of refugees from Cambodia, Laos, and Vietnam during the 1970s and thereafter.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The four temples within a ten-mile radius of Bayou La Batre, include Chua Chanh Giac, Wat Buddharaksa, and Wat Lao Phoutthavihan.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] The first community of adherents of the Baháʼí Faith in Alabama was founded in 1896 by Paul K.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Dealy, who moved from Chicago to Fairhope.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Baháʼí centers in Alabama exist in Birmingham, Huntsville, and Florence.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] In 2018, life expectancy in Alabama was 75.1 years, below the national average of 78.7 years and is the third lowest life expectancy in the country.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Factors that can cause lower life expectancy are maternal mortality, suicide, and gun crimes.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] A Centers for Disease Control and Prevention study in 2008 showed that obesity in Alabama is a problem, with most counties having more than 29% of adults obese, except for ten which had a rate between 26% and 29%.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Residents of the state, along with those in five other states, were least likely in the nation to be physically active during leisure time.
[src:alabama/alabama-p01] Alabama, and the southeastern U.S. in general, has one of the highest incidences of adult onset diabetes in the country, exceeding 10% of adults.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Bureau of Economic Analysis, in 2025, Alabama's total gross state product was $341.1 billion, and the state's per capita personal income was $59,677.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The state has invested in aerospace, education, health care, banking, and various heavy industries, including automobile manufacturing, mineral extraction, steel production and fabrication.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] By 2006, crop and animal production in Alabama was valued at $1.5 billion.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In contrast to the primarily agricultural economy of the previous century, this was only about one percent of the state's gross domestic product.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The number of private farms has declined at a steady rate since the 1960s, as land has been sold to developers, timber companies, and large farming conglomerates.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In 2025, 99.4% of Alabama businesses were small businesses and employed 46.0% of the state's workforce.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The state's seasonally adjusted unemployment rate was 5.8% in April 2015.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] This compared to a nationwide seasonally adjusted rate of 5.4%.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] As of May 2025, the unemployment rate was 3.3%.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama has no minimum wage and in February 2016 passed legislation preventing municipalities from setting one.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] As of 2018, Alabama has the sixth highest poverty rate among states in the U.S.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In 2017, United Nations Special Rapporteur Philip Alston toured parts of rural Alabama and observed environmental conditions that he said were poorer than anywhere he had seen in the developed world.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama's agricultural outputs include poultry and eggs, cattle, fish, plant nursery items, peanuts, cotton, grains such as corn and sorghum, vegetables, milk, soybeans, and peaches.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Although known as "The Cotton State", Alabama ranks between eighth and tenth in national cotton production, according to various reports, with Texas, Georgia and Mississippi comprising the top three.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Aquaculture is a large part of the economy of Alabama.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabamians began to practice aquaculture in the early 1960s.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] U.S. farm-raised catfish is the 8th most popular seafood product in America.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] By 2008, approximately 4,000 people in Alabama were employed by the catfish industry and Alabama produced 132 million pounds of catfish.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In 2020, Alabama produced 1⁄3 of the United States' farm-raised catfish.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The total 2020 sales of catfish raised in Alabama equaled $307 million but by 2020 the total employment of Alabamians fell to 2,442.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] From the early 2000s to 2020, the Alabamian catfish industry has declined from 250 farms and 4 processors to 66 farms and 2 processors.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Reasons for this decline include increased feed prices, catfish alternatives, COVID-19's impact on restaurant sales, disease, and fish size.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama's industrial outputs include iron and steel products (including cast-iron and steel pipe); paper, lumber, and wood products; mining (mostly coal); plastic products; cars and trucks; and apparel.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In addition, Alabama produces aerospace and electronic products, mostly in the Huntsville area, the location of NASA's George C.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Marshall Space Flight Center and the U.S.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Army Materiel Command, headquartered at Redstone Arsenal.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] A great deal of Alabama's economic growth since the 1990s has been due to the state's expanding automotive manufacturing industry.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Located in the state are Honda Manufacturing of Alabama, Hyundai Motor Manufacturing Alabama, Mercedes-Benz U.S.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] International, and Toyota Motor Manufacturing Alabama, as well as their various suppliers.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Since 1993, the automobile industry has generated more than 67,800 new jobs in the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama currently ranks 4th in the nation for vehicle exports.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Automakers accounted for approximately a third of the industrial expansion in the state in 2012.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The eight models produced at the state's auto factories totaled combined sales of 74,335 vehicles for 2012.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The strongest model sales during this period were the Hyundai Elantra compact car, the Mercedes-Benz GL-Class sport utility vehicle and the Honda Ridgeline sport utility truck.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Steel producers Outokumpu, Nucor, SSAB, ThyssenKrupp, and U.S.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Steel have facilities in Alabama and employ more than 10,000 people.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In May 2007, German steelmaker ThyssenKrupp selected Calvert in Mobile County for a 4.65 billion combined stainless and carbon steel processing facility.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] ThyssenKrupp's stainless steel division, Inoxum, including the stainless portion of the Calvert plant, was sold to Finnish stainless steel company Outokumpu in 2012.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The remaining portion of the ThyssenKrupp plant had final bids submitted by ArcelorMittal and Nippon Steel for $1.6 billion in March 2013.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Companhia Siderúrgica Nacional submitted a combined bid for the mill at Calvert, plus a majority stake in the ThyssenKrupp mill in Brazil, for $3.8 billion.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In July 2013, the plant was sold to ArcelorMittal and Nippon Steel.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The Hunt Refining Company, a subsidiary of Hunt Consolidated, Inc., is based in Tuscaloosa and operates a refinery there.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The company also operates terminals in Mobile, Melvin, and Moundville.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] JVC America, Inc. operates an optical disc replication and packaging plant in Tuscaloosa.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The Goodyear Tire and Rubber Company operates a large plant in Gadsden which employs about 1,400 people.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Construction of an Airbus A320 family aircraft assembly plant in Mobile was formally announced by Airbus CEO Fabrice Brégier from the Mobile Convention Center on July 2, 2012.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The plans include a $600 million factory at the Brookley Aeroplex for the assembly of the A319, A320 and A321 aircraft.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Construction began in 2013, with plans for it to become operable by 2015 and produce up to 50 aircraft per year by 2017.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The assembly plant is the company's first factory to be built within the United States.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] It was announced on February 1, 2013, that Airbus had hired Alabama-based Hoar Construction to oversee construction of the facility.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The factory officially opened on September 14, 2015, covering one million square feet on 53 acres of flat grassland.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] According to Business Insider, Alabama ranked 14th in most popular states to visit in 2014.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] An estimated 26 million tourists visited the state in 2017 and spent $14.3 billion, providing directly or indirectly 186,900 jobs in the state, which includes 362,000 International tourists spending $589 million.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Mobile is known for having the oldest organized Mardi Gras celebration in the United States, beginning in 1703.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] It was also host to the first formally organized Mardi Gras parade in the U.S. in 1830, a tradition that continues to this day.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Mardi Gras is an official state holiday in Mobile and Baldwin counties.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In 2018, Mobile's Mardi Gras parade was the state's top event, producing the most tourists with an attendance of 892,811.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Space & Rocket Center in Huntsville with an attendance of 849,981, followed by the Birmingham Zoo with 543,090.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Of the parks and natural destinations, Alabama's Gulf Coast topped the list with 6,700,000 visitors.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama has historically been a popular region for film shoots due to its diverse landscapes and contrast of environments.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Movies filmed in Alabama include *Close Encounters of the Third Kind*, *Get Out*, *42*, *Selma*, *Big Fish*, *The Final Destination*, *Due Date*, and *Need for Speed*.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] UAB Hospital, USA Health University Hospital, Huntsville Hospital, and Children's Hospital of Alabama are the only Level I trauma centers in Alabama.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] UAB is the largest state government employer in Alabama, with a workforce of about 18,000.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] A 2017 study found that Alabama had the least competitive health insurance market in the country, with Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Alabama having a market share of 84% followed by UnitedHealth Group at 7%.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Regions Financial Corporation is the largest bank headquartered in or operating in Alabama.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] PNC Financial Services and Wells Fargo also have a major presence in Alabama.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Wells Fargo has a regional headquarters, an operations center campus, and a $400 million data center in Birmingham.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Many smaller banks are also headquartered in the Birmingham area, including ServisFirst and New South Federal Savings Bank.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Birmingham also serves as the headquarters for several large investment management companies, including Harbert Management Corporation.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Telecommunications provider AT&T, formerly BellSouth, has a major presence in Alabama with several large offices in Birmingham.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Many technology companies are headquartered in Huntsville, such as ADTRAN, a network access company; Intergraph, a computer graphics company; and Avocent, an IT infrastructure company.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Brasfield & Gorrie, BE&K, Hoar Construction, and B.L.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Harbert International, based in Alabama and subsidiaries of URS Corporation, are all routinely are included in the Engineering News-Record lists of top design, international construction, and engineering firms.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The foundational document for Alabama's government is the Alabama Constitution, the current constitution was adopted in 2022.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The former Alabama constitution adopted in 1901 was, with over 850 amendments and almost 87,000 words, by some accounts the world's longest constitution and roughly forty times the length of the United States Constitution.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] There was a significant movement to rewrite and modernize Alabama's constitution.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The former constitution was particularly criticized for its complexity and length intentionally codifying segregation and racism.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama's government is divided into three coequal branches.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The legislative branch is the Alabama Legislature, a bicameral assembly composed of the Alabama House of Representatives, with 105 members, and the Alabama Senate, with 35 members.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The Legislature is responsible for writing, debating, passing, or defeating state legislation.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The Republican Party currently holds a majority in both houses of the Legislature.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The Legislature has the power to override a gubernatorial veto by a simple majority (most state Legislatures require a two-thirds majority to override a veto).
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Until 1964, the state elected state senators on a geographic basis by county, with one per county.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] It had not redistricted congressional districts since passage of its constitution in 1901; as a result, urbanized areas were grossly underrepresented.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] It had not changed legislative districts to reflect the decennial censuses, either.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] At that time, Alabama and many other states had to change their legislative districting, as many across the country had systems that underrepresented urban areas and districts.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] This had caused decades of underinvestment in such areas.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] For instance, Birmingham and Jefferson County taxes had supplied one-third of the state budget, but Jefferson County received only 1/67th of state services in funding.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Through the legislative delegations, the Alabama legislature kept control of county governments.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The executive branch is responsible for the execution and oversight of laws.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] It is headed by the governor of Alabama.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Other members of the executive branch include the cabinet, the lieutenant governor of Alabama, the Attorney General of Alabama, the Alabama Secretary of State, the Alabama State Treasurer, and the State Auditor of Alabama.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The current governor is Republican Kay Ivey.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The members of the Legislature take office immediately after the November elections.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Statewide officials, such as the governor, lieutenant governor, attorney general, and other constitutional officers, take office the following January.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The judiciary is responsible for interpreting the Constitution of Alabama and applying the law in state criminal and civil cases.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The state's highest court is the Supreme Court of Alabama.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama uses partisan elections to select judges.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Since the 1980s judicial campaigns have become increasingly politicized.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The current chief justice of the Alabama Supreme Court is Republican Tom Parker.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] All sitting justices on the Alabama Supreme Court are members of the Republican Party.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] There are two intermediate appellate courts, the Court of Civil Appeals and the Court of Criminal Appeals, and four trial courts: the circuit court (trial court of general jurisdiction), and the district, probate, and municipal courts.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama has the death penalty with authorized methods of execution that include the electric chair and the gas chamber.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Some critics believe the election of judges has contributed to an exceedingly high rate of executions.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama has the highest per capita death penalty rate in the country.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In some years, it imposes more death sentences than does Texas, a state which has a population five times larger.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] However, executions per capita are significantly higher in Texas.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Some of its cases have been highly controversial; the U.S.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Supreme Court has overturned 83 convictions in death penalty cases.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] It was the only state to allow judges to override jury decisions in whether or not to use a death sentence; in 10 cases judges overturned sentences of life imprisonment without parole that were voted unanimously by juries.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] This judicial authority was removed in April 2017.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] On May 14, 2019, Alabama passed the Human Life Protection Act, banning abortion at any stage of pregnancy unless there is a "serious health risk", with no exceptions for rape and incest.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The law subjects doctors who perform abortions with 10 to 99 years imprisonment.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The law was originally supposed to take effect the following November, but on October 29, 2019, U.S.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] District Judge Myron Thompson blocked the law from taking effect due to it being in conflict with the 1973 U.S.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, Judge Thompson lifted the injunction, allowing the law to go into effect.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama is one of five to not operate a state lottery and one of just two states, the other being Utah, that prohibits the creation of state lotteries in their constitutions.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Taxes are collected by the Alabama Department of Revenue.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama levies a 2%, 4%, or 5% personal income tax, depending on the amount earned and filing status.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Taxpayers are allowed to deduct their federal income tax from their Alabama state tax, even if taking the standard deduction; those who itemize can also deduct FICA (the Social Security and Medicare tax).
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The state's general sales tax rate is 4%.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Sales tax rates for cities and counties are also added to purchases.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] For example, the total sales tax rate in Mobile County is 10% and there is an additional restaurant tax of 1%, which means a diner in Mobile County would pay an 11% tax on a meal.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In 2020, sales and excise taxes in Alabama accounted for 38% of all state and local revenue.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama gradually reduced the grocery tax to 2% between 2024 and 2025.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In April 2026, Alabama paused the grocery tax for the months of May and July of that year.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The corporate income tax rate in Alabama is 6.5%.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The overall federal, state, and local tax burden in Alabama ranks the state as the second least tax-burdened state in the country.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Property taxes of 0.40% of assessed value per year, are the second-lowest in the U.S., after Hawaii.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The state constitution currently requires a voter referendum to raise property taxes.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Historically, an Alabama excise tax "on the storage, use or other consumption in this state of tangible personal property purchased at retail for storage, use or other consumption in this state" was the focus of a 1941 U S Supreme Court ruling, *Curry v United States*.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Each county has its own elected legislative branch, usually called the county commission.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] It also has limited executive authority in the county.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Because of the constraints of the Alabama Constitution, which centralizes power in the state legislature, only seven counties (Jefferson, Lee, Mobile, Madison, Montgomery, Shelby, and Tuscaloosa) in the state have limited home rule.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Instead, most counties in the state must lobby the Local Legislation Committee of the state legislature to get simple local policies approved, ranging from waste disposal to land use zoning.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The state legislature has retained power over local governments by refusing to pass a constitutional amendment establishing home rule for counties, as recommended by the 1973 Alabama Constitutional Commission.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Legislative delegations retain certain powers over each county.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] United States Supreme Court decisions in *Baker v.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Carr* (1964) required that both houses have districts established on the basis of population, and redistricted after each census, to implement the principle of "one man, one vote".
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Before that, each county was represented by one state senator, leading to under-representation in the state senate for more urbanized, populous counties.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The rural bias of the state legislature, which had also failed to redistrict seats in the state house, affected politics well into the 20th century, failing to recognize the rise of industrial cities and urbanized areas.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] "The lack of home rule for counties in Alabama has resulted in the proliferation of local legislation permitting counties to do things not authorized by the state constitution.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama's constitution has been amended more than 700 times, and almost one-third of the amendments are local in nature, applying to only one county or city.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama is an alcoholic beverage control state, meaning the state government holds a monopoly on the sale of alcohol.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The Alabama Alcoholic Beverage Control Board controls the sale and distribution of alcoholic beverages in the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] A total of 25 of the 67 counties are "dry counties" which ban the sale of alcohol, and there are many dry municipalities in counties which permit alcohol sales.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] During Reconstruction following the American Civil War, Alabama was occupied by federal troops of the Third Military District under General John Pope.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In 1874, the political coalition of white Democrats known as the Redeemers took control of the state government from the Republicans, in part by suppressing the black vote through violence, fraud, and intimidation.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] After 1890, a coalition of White Democratic politicians passed laws to segregate and disenfranchise African American residents, a process completed in provisions of the 1901 constitution.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Provisions which disenfranchised blacks resulted in excluding many poor Whites.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] By 1941 more Whites than Blacks had been disenfranchised: 600,000 to 520,000.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The total effects were greater on the black community, as almost all its citizens were disfranchised and relegated to separate and unequal treatment under the law.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] From 1901 through the 1960s, the state did not redraw election districts as population grew and shifted within the state during urbanization and industrialization of certain areas.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] As counties were the basis of election districts, the result was a rural minority that dominated state politics through nearly three-quarters of the century, until a series of federal court cases required redistricting in 1972 to meet equal representation.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama state politics gained nationwide and international attention in the 1950s and 1960s during the civil rights movement, when whites bureaucratically, and at times violently, resisted protests for electoral and social reform.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Governor George Wallace, the state's only four-term governor, was a controversial figure who vowed to maintain segregation.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Only after passage of the federal Civil Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965 did African Americans regain the ability to exercise suffrage, among other civil rights.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In many jurisdictions, they continued to be excluded from representation by at-large electoral systems, which allowed the majority of the population to dominate elections.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Some changes at the county level have occurred following court challenges to establish single-member districts that enable a more diverse representation among county boards.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In 2007, the Alabama Legislature passed, and Republican governor Bob Riley signed a resolution expressing "profound regret" over slavery and its lingering impact.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In a symbolic ceremony, the bill was signed in the Alabama State Capitol, which housed Congress of the Confederate States of America.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In 2010, Republicans won control of both houses of the legislature for the first time in 136 years.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] As of February 2023, there are a total of 3,707,233 registered voters, with 3,318,679 active, and the others inactive in the state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The 2023 *American Values Atlas* by Public Religion Research Institute found that a majority of Alabama residents support same-sex marriage.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] With the disfranchisement of Blacks in 1901, the state became part of the "Solid South", a system in which the Democratic Party operated as effectively the only viable political party in every Southern state.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] For nearly a hundred years local and state elections in Alabama were decided in the Democratic Party primary, with generally only token Republican challengers running in the general election.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Since the mid- to late 20th century, however, white conservatives started shifting to the Republican Party.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In Alabama, majority-white districts are now expected to regularly elect Republican candidates to federal, state and local office.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Members of the nine seats on the Supreme Court of Alabama and all ten seats on the state appellate courts are elected to office.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Until 1994, no Republicans held any of the court seats.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In that general election, the then-incumbent chief justice, Ernest C.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Hornsby, refused to leave office after losing the election by approximately 3,000 votes to Republican Perry O.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Hornsby sued Alabama and defiantly remained in office for nearly a year before finally giving up the seat after losing in court.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The Democrats lost the last of the nineteen court seats in August 2011 with the resignation of the last Democrat on the bench.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In the early 21st century, Republicans hold all seven of the statewide elected executive branch offices.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Republicans hold six of the eight elected seats on the Alabama State Board of Education.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In 2010, Republicans took large majorities of both chambers of the state legislature, giving them control of that body for the first time in 136 years.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The last remaining statewide Democrat, who served on the Alabama Public Service Commission, was defeated in 2012.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Only three Republican lieutenant governors have been elected since the end of Reconstruction, when Republicans generally represented Reconstruction government, including the newly emancipated freedmen who had gained the franchise.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The three GOP lieutenant governors are Steve Windom (1999–2003), Kay Ivey (2011–2017), and Will Ainsworth (2019–present).
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Many metropolitan and suburban counties have voters who are majority Democrats, resulting in local elections being decided in the Democratic primary.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Similarly, most rural counties are majority-Republican and elections are effectively decided in the Republican primary.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] However, since local governments in Alabama are weaker than in other parts of the country, Republicans have the upper hand in government.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama's 67 county sheriffs are elected in partisan, at-large races, and Republicans retain the vast majority of those posts.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The current split is 18 Democrats, and 49 Republicans as of 2023.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] However, most of the Democratic sheriffs preside over urban and more populated counties.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The majority of Republican sheriffs have been elected in the more rural counties with lower population.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] As of 2025, the state of Alabama has 11 African-American sheriffs.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The state's two U.S. senators are Katie Britt and Tommy Tuberville, both of whom are Republican.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] House of Representatives, the state is represented by seven members, five of whom are Republicans (Mike Rogers, Robert Aderholt, Dale Strong, Barry Moore, and Gary Palmer) and two Democrats (Terri Sewell and Shomari Figures).
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Public primary and secondary education in Alabama is under the purview of the Alabama State Board of Education as well as local oversight by 67 county school boards and 60 city boards of education.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Together, 1,496 individual schools provide education for 744,637 elementary and secondary students.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Public school funding is appropriated through the Alabama Legislature through the Education Trust Fund.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] That represented an increase of $444,736,387 over the previous fiscal year.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In 2007, more than 82 percent of schools made Adequate Yearly Progress (AYP) toward student proficiency under the National No Child Left Behind law, using measures determined by the state of Alabama.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] While Alabama's public education system has improved in recent decades, it lags behind in achievement compared to other states.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Census data (2000), Alabama's high school graduation rate (75%) is the fourth lowest in the U.S.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] (after Kentucky, Louisiana and Mississippi).
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The largest educational gains were among people with some college education but without degrees.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] According to National Assessment of Educational Progress (NEAP), Alabama ranks 39 in reading and 40 in math among fourth-grade students in the rankings from 2022.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Generally prohibited in the West at large, school corporal punishment is not unusual in Alabama, with 27,260 public school students paddled at least one time, according to government data for the 2011–2012 school year.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The rate of school corporal punishment in Alabama is surpassed by only Mississippi and Arkansas.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama's programs of higher education include 14 four-year public universities, two-year community colleges, and 17 private, undergraduate and graduate universities.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Public, post-secondary education in Alabama is overseen by the Alabama Commission on Higher Education and the Alabama Department of Postsecondary Education.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Colleges and universities in Alabama offer degree programs from two-year associate degrees to a multitude of doctoral level programs.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The largest single campus in Alabama is Tuskegee University with 5000 acres.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The largest student body is the University of Alabama, located in Tuscaloosa, with 42,360 students enrolled for fall 2025.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Troy University was the largest institution in the state in 2010, with an enrollment of 29,689 students across four Alabama campuses (Troy, Dothan, Montgomery, and Phenix City), as well as sixty learning sites in seventeen other states and eleven other countries.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The oldest institutions are the public University of North Alabama in Florence and the Catholic Church-affiliated Spring Hill College in Mobile, both founded in 1830.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] News & World Report*, Alabama had three universities ranked in the top 100 Public Schools in America (Auburn University at 47, University of Alabama at Birmingham (UAB) at 76, and University of Alabama at 91).
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] News & World Report*, Alabama had four tier one universities (Auburn University, University of Alabama at Birmingham (UAB), University of Alabama and University of Alabama in Huntsville).
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Major newspapers include *Birmingham News*, Mobile *Press-Register*, and *Montgomery Advertiser*.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama literature is characterized by themes of race and issues of gender and war, and is influenced by events such as the American Civil War, the Reconstruction era, the civil rights movement, and the Vietnam War.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Some notable examples of Alabama literature include Harper Lee's *To Kill a Mockingbird*, Winston Groom's *Forrest Gump*, Fannie Flagg's *Fried Green Tomatoes at the Whistle Stop Cafe*, and the biographies of Rosa Parks and Martin Luther King Jr.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama has several professional and semi-professional sports teams, including three minor league baseball teams.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The Talladega Superspeedway motorsports complex hosts a series of NASCAR events.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] It has a seating capacity of 143,000 and is the thirteenth largest stadium in the world and sixth largest stadium in America.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Also, the Barber Motorsports Park has hosted IndyCar Series and Rolex Sports Car Series races.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The ATP Birmingham was a World Championship Tennis tournament held from 1973 to 1980.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama has hosted several professional golf tournaments, such as the 1984 and 1990 PGA Championship at Shoal Creek, the Barbasol Championship (PGA Tour), the Mobile LPGA Tournament of Champions, Airbus LPGA Classic, and Yokohama Tire LPGA Classic (LPGA Tour), and The Tradition (Champions Tour).
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] College football is extremely popular in Alabama, particularly the University of Alabama Crimson Tide and Auburn University Tigers, rivals in the Southeastern Conference.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Alabama averages over 100,000 fans per game and Auburn averages over 80,000—both numbers among the top twenty in the nation.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Bryant–Denny Stadium is the home of the Alabama football team, and has a seating capacity of 101,821, and is the fifth largest stadium in America.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Jordan-Hare Stadium is the home field of the Auburn football team and seats up to 87,451.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Protective Stadium is home of the UAB Blazers football program and the Birmingham Bowl.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Opening in 2020, Hancock Whitney Stadium in Mobile is the home of the University of South Alabama football team, and serves as the home of the Reese's Senior Bowl, the AHSAA North/South All-star Game, and the LendingTree Bowl; the stadium seats 25,450.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In 2009, Bryant–Denny Stadium and Jordan-Hare Stadium became the homes of the Alabama High School Athletic Association state football championship games, after previously being held at Legion Field in Birmingham.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] For rail transport, Amtrak schedules the *Crescent*, a daily passenger train, running from New York to New Orleans with station stops at Anniston, Birmingham, and Tuscaloosa.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The *Mardi Gras Service* operates daily between Mobile and New Orleans; the Mobile terminus is its only Alabama stop.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] I-22 enters the state from Mississippi and connects Birmingham with Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] In addition, there are currently five auxiliary interstate routes in the state: I-165 in Mobile, I-359 in Tuscaloosa, I-459 around Birmingham, I-565 in Decatur and Huntsville, and I-759 in Gadsden.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] A sixth route, I-685, will be formed when I-85 is rerouted along a new southern bypass of Montgomery.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] A proposed northern bypass of Birmingham will be designated as I-422.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Since a direct connection from I-22 to I-422 will not be possible, I-222 has been proposed, as well.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] Highways also pass through the state, such as U.S.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] There are four toll roads in the state: Montgomery Expressway in Montgomery; Northport/Tuscaloosa Western Bypass in Tuscaloosa and Northport; Emerald Mountain Expressway in Wetumpka; and Beach Express in Orange Beach.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The Port of Mobile, Alabama's only saltwater port, is a large seaport on the Gulf of Mexico with inland waterway access to the Midwest by way of the Tennessee–Tombigbee Waterway.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The Port of Mobile was ranked 12th by tons of traffic in the United States during 2009.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The newly expanded container terminal at the Port of Mobile was ranked as the 25th busiest for container traffic in the nation during 2011.
[src:alabama/alabama-p02] The state's other ports are on rivers with access to the Gulf of Mexico.
